'''''Lethocerus insulanus''''' is a species of [[giant water bug]] of the family [[Belostomatidae]]. Its common name is the '''giant water bug''', but it is also called the '''electric light bug''' or '''giant fishkiller'''. These names are also used for various other members of the family, including the other Australian species, ''[[Lethocerus distinctifemur|L. distinctifemur]]'', which is similar to ''L. insulanus''.<ref name=Goodwyn>P. J. Perez-Goodwyn (2006). ''Taxonomic revision of the subfamily Lethocerinae Lauck & Menke (Heteroptera: Belostomatidae)". Stuttgarter Beiträge zur Naturkunde.'' A (Biologie) 695: 1–71.</ref>

==Distribution==
The species is found in north-eastern Australia, particularly [[Queensland]], but also northern [[New South Wales]] and the [[Northern Territory]]. It is also present in the [[Philippines]] and parts of [[Melanesia]] including [[New Caledonia]] and [[Papua New Guinea]].<ref>[http://www.environment.gov.au/biodiversity/abrs/online-resources/fauna/afd/taxa/Lethocerus%20(Lethocerus)%20insulanus Species ''Lethocerus (Lethocerus) insulanus'' (Montandon, 1898)], ''Australian Faunal Directory'', Department of the Environment, 30 November 2012.</ref>

It lives in still, freshwater bodies such as lakes.<ref name=ausmuseum>[http://australianmuseum.net.au/Giant-Water-Bug Giant Water Bug], Australian Museum.</ref>

==Description==
''Lethocerus insulanus'' is very large, with adults typically reaching a length of {{convert|5|-|7|cm|in|abbr=on}}.<ref name=Goodwyn/> It uses a posterior syphon like a snorkel to breathe underwater while hunting.<ref name=ausmuseum />

